[src:1924-colored-world-series/1921-hilldale-club-season] The **1921 Hilldale Club baseball team** represented the Hilldale Club as an independent during the 1921 baseball season.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1921-hilldale-club-season] The team compiled a 28–18–1 (.606) record and was recognized as the champion of the Eastern independent teams.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1921-hilldale-club-season] Bill Francis was Hilldale's player-manager.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1921-hilldale-club-season] The team played its home games at Hilldale Park in Darby, Pennsylvania, a Philadelphia suburb.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1921-hilldale-club-season] The team included two players who were late inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame: third baseman Judy Johnson and catcher Louis Santop.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1921-hilldale-club-season] The team's leading pitchers were Dick Whitworth (10–5, 2.49 ERA, 61 strikeouts), Phil Cockrell (8–5, 3.84 ERA), and Connie Rector (5–1, 3.25 ERA).
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-hilldale-club-season] The **1923 Hilldale Club baseball team** represented the Hilldale Club in the Eastern Colored League (ECL) during the 1923 baseball season.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-hilldale-club-season] The team compiled a 40–21–1 (.653) record and won the ECL pennant.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-hilldale-club-season] John Henry Lloyd was Hilldale's player-manager.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-hilldale-club-season] The team included four players who were late inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame: manager/shortstop John Henry Lloyd, third baseman Judy Johnson, catcher Biz Mackey, and catcher Louis Santop.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-hilldale-club-season] The team's leading pitchers were Nip Winters (10–3, 2.36 ERA, 95 strikeouts) and Red Ryan (9–5, 2.48 ERA).
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-kansas-city-monarchs-season] The **1923 Kansas City Monarchs baseball team** competed in the Negro National League during the 1923 baseball season.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-kansas-city-monarchs-season] The Monarchs compiled a 61–37 (.622) record and won the Negro National League championship.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-kansas-city-monarchs-season] The team played its home games at Muehlebach Field and Association Park in Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1923-kansas-city-monarchs-season] The team's leading pitchers were Bullet Rogan (16–11, 2.94 ERA, 151 strikeouts in 248 innings pitched) and Reuben Currie (15–9, 3.24 ERA, 119 strikeouts in 213 innings pitched).
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The **1924 Colored World Series** was a best-of-nine match-up between the Negro National League champion Kansas City Monarchs and the Eastern Colored League champion Hilldale.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] In a ten-game series, the Monarchs narrowly defeated Hilldale 5 games to 4, with one tie game.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] It was the first World Series between the respective champions of the NNL and ECL.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] It was the second year of existence for the ECL, but no agreement could be reached in 1923 for a postseason series, owing primarily to unresolved disputes between the leagues.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Five members of the Baseball Hall of Fame participated in the series: Biz Mackey, Judy Johnson, and Louis Santop played for Hilldale, while Bullet Rogan and José Méndez played for the Monarchs.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Wilkinson was also inducted into the Hall.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Rogan pitched an 8-hitter, holding Hilldale scoreless until two out in the ninth.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Warfield's bases-loaded error in the sixth allowed the Monarchs to score two, and aided by Cockrell's three errors in the same inning, opened up a five-run inning for the Monarchs.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] , but instead used National League Park, home field of the Philadelphia Phillies, for the first two games, owing to its larger capacity.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Bill McCall could not get through the first inning, facing only three men and recording no outs before Bill "Plunk" Drake came in to relieve.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Hilldale led 9-0 by the end of the third.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] shut out the normally high-scoring Monarchs on four singles.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The Monarchs took a one-run lead into the bottom of the ninth and again into the bottom of the twelfth, but were unable to put Hilldale away.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] William Bell pitched 12 innings for no decision; he played the thirteenth inning in right field, as Rogan came in from center field to pitch the thirteenth inning.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Monarch fielding errors in the fifth and ninth innings allowed Hilldale to stay in the game.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] received three intentional walks during the game.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The game was called on account of darkness after thirteen innings.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] , on account of Pennsylvania's blue laws, which did not allow professional baseball games on Sundays.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] After yesterday's tie game, another game was rescheduled for the following day.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Before a sparse weekday crowd, former Monarch Rube Currie relieved Red Ryan with one out in the third and the Monarchs leading 3–0, and shut them out the rest of the game.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Hilldale tied the game in the third on two base hits, a walk, and three steals, including Otto Briggs' steal of home.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Two walks and two errors helped score Hilldale's winning run with none out in the ninth.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] 's three-run inside-the-park home run with one out in the ninth shocked the crowd into silence and provided the difference in the game.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] A controversial umpire call and three defensive misplays helped set the table for Johnson's heroics.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Until the fatal ninth, the game had been a classic pitchers' duel between staff aces Winters and Rogan.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Winters finished the game with a flourish, retiring 25 of the last 26 men he faced.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Rube Foster had originally scheduled games Five, Six and Seven for his own ballpark, but Kansas City ownership and fans strenuously objected to losing such lucrative dates, and Foster relented.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Phil Cockrell started the game for Hilldale, but was driven from the mound in the first inning, allowing four runs.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] pitched the remainder of the game, but tired in the eighth when the Monarchs scored the tie-breaking run.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Nip Winters pitched twelve innings and took the loss, while Méndez pitched brilliantly in relief for the win.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] stole home in the fourth inning to start the Monarchs' scoring.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Bullet Rogan did not hit the ball out of the infield, but still managed to get three hits, score one run, and drive in the winning tally in the twelfth inning.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] In one of Negro league baseball's legendary games, the Monarchs rallied for three runs in the ninth to stun Hilldale.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] foul popup, Duncan lined a single past Mackey that scored the tying and winning runs.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Also legendary was the vicious verbal assault that Warfield launched against Santop following the loss, laying blame for the loss squarely at Santop's feet.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Santop and others were already in tears in their locker room following the game, and it is one of Blackball's legends that Santop never recovered from the humiliation of Warfield's tirade.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Starting and completing his fourth game of the series, Nip Winters won for the third time to tie the series.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] William Bell started for Kansas City, but was shelled with none out in the fifth inning when Hilldale tied the score 2-2.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Drake pitched creditably until tiring in the ninth, when Hilldale scored two to win.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The Series was now tied for the third time.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] He matched Hilldale starter Scrip Lee zero for zero for seven full innings until Lee tired in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Lee changed from his normal submarine delivery to an overhand style in that inning, and the Monarchs scored five runs off of him, including one by Méndez himself.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] When Hilldale went out in the ninth, the Monarchs had won the first Colored World Series.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-hilldale-club-season] The **1924 Hilldale Club baseball team** represented the Hilldale Club in the Eastern Colored League (ECL) during the 1924 baseball season.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-hilldale-club-season] The team compiled a 47–26 (.644) record and won the ECL pennant.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-hilldale-club-season] Frank Warfield was Hilldale's player-manager.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-hilldale-club-season] The team played its home games at Hilldale Park in Yeadon, Pennsylvania, a Philadelphia suburb.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-hilldale-club-season] The team included at least three players who were late inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame: third baseman Judy Johnson, catcher Biz Mackey, and catcher Louis Santop.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1924 throughout the world.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-in-baseball] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-in-baseball] A loose confederation of teams existed that were not part of either established leagues.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-kansas-city-monarchs-season] The **1924 Kansas City Monarchs baseball team** competed in the Negro National League during the 1924 baseball season.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-kansas-city-monarchs-season] The Monarchs compiled a 57–22 (.722) record and won the Negro National League championship.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-kansas-city-monarchs-season] The team played its home games at Muehlebach Field in Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-kansas-city-monarchs-season] The team's leading pitchers were Bullet Rogan (16–5, 3.14 ERA, 101 strikeouts in 175 innings pithed) and William Bell (9–2, 3.75 ERA).
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The **1924 World Series** was the championship series of the 1924 Major League Baseball season.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The 21st edition of the World Series was a best-of-seven playoff matching the American League (AL) champion Washington Senators against the National League (NL) champion New York Giants, with the Senators defeating the Giants in seven games to win their first championship in club history.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Washington, D.C.-based team.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The Giants became the first team to play in four consecutive World Series, winning in 1921–1922 and losing in 1923–1924, and their veteran manager, John McGraw, made his ninth and final World Series appearance.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The deciding game of the Series was decided in extra innings, the second such occurrence in MLB history (the first had occurred in 1912).
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Walter Johnson, nearing the end of his playing career at age 36, made his first ever World Series appearance, having completed his first 20-win season since 1919 (with 23 wins).
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] He lost both of his two starts, but was awarded a win in Game 7 with a relief appearance in which he held the Giants scoreless over the final four innings, helping the Senators secure their first championship.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Game 7 is widely considered one of the most dramatic in World Series history.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Johnson struck out 12 Giants batters in Game 1 in a losing cause.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Although that total matched Ed Walsh's number in the 1906 World Series, it came in 12 innings.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Johnson struck out only nine in the first nine innings.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] In Game 7, with the Senators behind 3–1 in the eighth, Bucky Harris hit a routine ground ball to third which hit a pebble and took a bad hop over Giants third baseman Freddie Lindstrom.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Two runners scored on the play, tying the score at three.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Walter Johnson then came in to pitch the ninth, and held the Giants scoreless into extra innings.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] With the score still 3–3, Washington came up in the 12th.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] With one out, and runners on first and second, Earl McNeely hit another grounder at Lindstrom, and again the ball took a bad hop, scoring Muddy Ruel with the Series-winning run.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] This was the first World Series to use the 2–3–2 home game pattern, which would be adapted as the permanent format beginning the following year.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] This was the Senators' only World Series championship victory during the franchise's time in Washington.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] In 1961, the Senators relocated to Minnesota and were rebranded as the Twins, and subsequently won the World Series in 1987 and in 1991.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] This would be the last World Series win for a Washington based team until the Washington Nationals, who were originally the Montreal Expos, won the World Series in 2019, 95 years after the Senators' only triumph.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] In 2020, ESPN named it the third greatest World Series of all-time.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The Senators tied it at 2–2 with a run in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The Giants scored two in the top of the 12th off the Big Train; Washington fought back for a run in the bottom of the inning, but left the tying run on third.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Washington fought back early in the game, scoring 3 runs in 5 innings.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] But the Giants would quickly fight back in the final three frames to tie the game as it went to the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] With Joe Judge representing the potential winning run and 1 out, Roger Peckinpaugh hit a double to win the game and tie the series.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Ossie Bluege, the only man reliever Claude Jonnard faced, drew a bases-loaded walk to make it 6-4.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Mule Watson then came in to nail down the last two outs.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Rosy Ryan's fourth-inning home run is to date the only World Series home run by a relief pitcher and the only postseason home run by a relief pitcher until Travis Wood in 2016.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Goose Goslin had a big game for the Senators, with three singles and a home run to go 4-for-4 and drive in four runs.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Johnson again pitched a complete game but the Giants recorded 13 hits off him, taking a 3–2 lead in the Series.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Bentley broke a 1–1 tie in the fifth with a two-run home run, the second homer by a New York pitcher in the Series after Rosy Ryan's in Game 3.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Both Washington runs scored on a single in the fifth inning by manager Bucky Harris.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Tom Zachary won his second game of the series, deadlocking the series at three games each.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The unheralded Curly Ogden was given the Game 7 start for Washington – it was his only World Series appearance.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] He struck out a batter and walked one, and then was pulled for George Mogridge.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] It was later revealed that manager Bucky Harris started righthander Ogden so that the Giants would be locked into their "righthanded" lineup, before he switched to the lefthander Mogridge.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] With the Senators trailing 3–1 in the eighth inning with bases loaded and two outs, Bucky Harris hit a "bad hop" ground ball to third, that reportedly struck a pebble, which Freddie Lindstrom failed to catch (no error was charged).
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] As a result, two runs scored for a 3–3 tie.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] In the ninth inning, Walter Johnson would step up as pitcher and pitch four scoreless innings.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] In the bottom of the 12th inning, Giants catcher Hank Gowdy stepped on his own discarded mask while trying to catch a Muddy Ruel foul pop-up, and dropped the ball for an error.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Given a second chance in the at-bat, Ruel doubled.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Johnson reached first on another error, and with Ruel on second and Johnson on first, Earl McNeely hit a "bad hop" ground ball to Lindstrom that was almost identical to Harris' eighth inning hit.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] Lindstrom again failed to catch the ball (reportedly hitting the same pebble that was struck four innings earlier) as it bounced over him into left field, and Ruel scored the series-winning run.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The game holds the record as the longest Game 7 (by innings) in MLB postseason history.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] It was also the first World Series Game 7 to be decided in extra innings (although the 1912 series ended with a ten-inning Game 8), and the last until 1991.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] In 2014, on the Series' 90th anniversary, the Library of Congress acquired a newsreel of highlight footage from Game 7, including McNeely's Series-winning base hit.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] CNN subsequently released this footage on its website.
[src:1924-colored-world-series/1924-world-series] The next time a Washington team won the World Series would come 95 years later in 2019, when the Washington Nationals did so against the Houston Astros.
